      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A newborn is brought in for evaluation immediately after delivery. The baby is stable with normal vital signs, but upon physical examination, a fluid-filled sac is observed on the baby&#39;s back. Based on the clinical presentation and the image provided, the condition is diagnosed as a neural tube defect. The concerned mother inquires about the underlying cause and the pattern of inheritance for this condition. What is the most appropriate response to provide?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/04/30/1_RuPkNAC.jpg\" style=\"height:228px; width:266px\" /></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1205963",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32728,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Multifactorial Inheritance</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Neural tube defects </strong>(NTDs) like <strong>spina bifida </strong>(which the described fluid-filled sac might represent) are best understood as <strong>multifactorial in origin</strong>. This means that both <strong>genetic and environmental factors </strong>play a role in their development. While there may be a <strong>genetic predisposition</strong>, factors such as <strong>maternal folic acid intake before conception </strong>and <strong>during pregnancy </strong>significantly influence the risk of NTDs.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Autosomal dominant Inheritance:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Autosomal dominant inheritance <strong>implies that the trait </strong>or <strong>condition is caused by a dominant allele </strong>on <strong>one of the autosomal chromosomes </strong>(non-sex chromosomes).</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In the context of neural tube defects, <strong>autosomal dominant inheritance </strong>is <strong>not a common mode of transmission </strong>for these conditions.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Mitochondrial Inheritance:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Mitochondrial inheritance involves the <strong>transmission of genetic traits </strong>through the <strong>mitochondria</strong>, which are <strong>structures outside the cell nucleus</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Neural tube defects </strong>are <strong>not </strong>typically <strong>associated with mitochondrial inheritance.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Autosomal recessive:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Autosomal recessive inheritance occurs when a <strong>person inherits two copies of a recessive allele </strong>for a <strong>particular gene</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">This mode of inheritance is not commonly associated with neural tube defects.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Neural tube defects </strong>(NTDs) are <strong>congenital malformations </strong>that <strong>occur during the development of the neural tube </strong>in the <strong>embryo</strong>. Examples of NTDs include conditions like spina bifida and anencephaly.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition Page No-4226.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
