      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Keep it moist by applying Meningomyelocele covered with sterile saline soaked gauze to prevent it from drying, trauma and infection.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>C:</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">For a child with a <strong>meningomyelocele, </strong>it is<strong> crucial to prevent </strong>the sac from <strong>drying out and to protect it from trauma and infection before surgical repair</strong>. This is typically done by covering the lesion with <strong>sterile saline-soaked gauze</strong>. Keeping the area <strong>moist helps maintain the integrity of the sac </strong>and the tissue within it,<strong> reducing the risk of infection </strong>and further damage.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Allowing the sac to dry could lead to<strong> tearing and an increased risk of infection</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">While urgent surgery is important, it is not the only management option before the operation.<strong> Pre-operative care is essential to ensure the best possible surgical outcome. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Phototherapy </strong>has<strong> no </strong>proven benefit in<strong> reducing the size of a meningomyelocele </strong>and is not part of the pre-operative care for this condition. Phototherapy is used in neonatal jaundice</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Meningomyelocele </strong>should be always covered with <strong>sterile saline soaked gauze to prevent it from drying, trauma and infection</strong>. This approach is consistent with the<strong> standard care for meningomyelocele to create a moist environment that aids in wound healing.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition,Page No-11980. </span></span></strong></p>",
